/* Teach me from the ground up: FE-TS (auto-assembled) */
enh({
  "structural-typing": {"teach":"<p>At its core, structural typing means TypeScript judges a value by its <strong>shape</strong>, not its <strong>name</strong>. If an object has all the properties the target needs, with the right types, it fits — and TypeScript never asks \"but were you <em>declared</em> to be this kind of thing?\"</p><div class=\"analogy\"><p>Think of a power outlet. The wall doesn't care whether you plug in a lamp, a charger, or a blender — it only cares that the prongs match the holes. That's structural typing. The opposite, <em>nominal</em> typing (Java, C#), is like a nightclub bouncer with a guest list: even if you look exactly like an invited guest, you don't get in unless your <em>name</em> is on the list.</p></div><h4>What this buys you, and what it costs</h4><p>The win is ergonomics. You can pass a plain object literal anywhere an interface is expected — no <code>implements</code>, no ceremony. A class that happens to have a <code>meow()</code> method satisfies a <code>Cat</code> interface even if it never heard of <code>Cat</code>. This is why TypeScript feels so frictionless for everyday JavaScript objects.</p><p>The cost is that two <em>semantically different</em> types with the same shape become interchangeable. A <code>Meters</code> type and a <code>Feet</code> type, both just <code>number</code>, are freely swappable — and the compiler shrugs while you mix units and crash a Mars probe.</p><h4>The one exception: excess property checking</h4><p>There is a deliberate carve-out. When you assign a <strong>fresh object literal</strong> directly, TypeScript runs <strong>excess property checking</strong> and flags properties that aren't in the target type. This catches typos like <code>{ collor: 'red' }</code> that pure structural rules would happily wave through (extra properties don't normally break shape compatibility). Note it only fires on fresh literals — assign through a variable first and the check disappears.</p><h4>Getting nominal guarantees back</h4><p>Sometimes you <em>want</em> the bouncer. The trick is a <strong>branded type</strong>: intersect your type with a unique \"phantom\" property that exists only at compile time.</p><ul><li><code>type UserId = string & { readonly __brand: 'UserId' }</code></li><li>A raw <code>string</code> lacks the <code>__brand</code> tag, so it's no longer assignable to <code>UserId</code>.</li><li>You mint values through a controlled function (<code>toUserId</code>) that asserts the brand. The brand is purely structural-typing trickery used to <em>defeat</em> structural typing — there's no runtime cost.</li></ul><p>This is how teams stop themselves from passing an <code>OrderId</code> where a <code>UserId</code> belongs, even though both are strings underneath.</p><div class=\"key\"><p>TypeScript accepts a value when its shape matches the target — names and <code>implements</code> are irrelevant. That makes plain objects effortless, but when you need identity (IDs, units), reach for branded types to manufacture a nominal distinction the structural system will respect.</p></div>"},
  "type-vs-interface": {"teach":"<p>At its core, <code>type</code> and <code>interface</code> are two ways to give a name to a type. For describing a plain object shape they're almost interchangeable — but they differ in two decisive ways: <strong>interfaces can re-open and merge</strong>, and <strong>type aliases can describe far more than objects</strong>.</p><h4>Interfaces merge; type aliases are closed</h4><p>If you declare an <code>interface</code> twice with the same name in the same scope, TypeScript <strong>combines</strong> them into one — this is <em>declaration merging</em>.</p><ul><li><code>interface W { a: number }</code> then <code>interface W { b: number }</code> yields <code>{ a; b }</code>.</li><li>Try the same with <code>type</code> and you get a hard \"Duplicate identifier\" error. Type aliases are sealed the moment you write them.</li></ul><p>This isn't a quirk — it's the whole mechanism behind augmenting global types or a library's types (adding <code>user</code> to Express's <code>Request</code>). Only interfaces can do this.</p><div class=\"analogy\"><p>An <code>interface</code> is like a shared Google Doc: anyone can re-open it later and add a paragraph, and everyone sees the combined result. A <code>type</code> alias is like a printed-and-laminated card: it says exactly one thing forever, but it can say <em>anything</em> — a poem, a chart, a union of options — not just a list of fields.</p></div><h4>Type aliases describe anything</h4><p>A <code>type</code> can express things an <code>interface</code> simply cannot:</p><ul><li>Unions: <code>type U = 'x' | 'y'</code></li><li>Tuples: <code>type Pair = [number, number]</code></li><li>Primitives, mapped types, conditional types, template literal types.</li></ul><p>An interface can only ever describe an object/function shape (and extend others). So the moment you need a union or a computed type, you reach for <code>type</code>.</p><h4>Which should you pick?</h4><p>A practical rule: <strong>prefer <code>interface</code> for public, extendable object contracts</strong> (library APIs, things third parties may augment) and <strong>use <code>type</code> for unions, tuples, and computed/derived types</strong>. There's also a mild performance angle — the checker caches interface instances by name, so large extension hierarchies can resolve slightly more efficiently as interfaces than as deeply intersected type aliases.</p><h4>The trap</h4><p>Don't believe they're fully interchangeable. The two non-overlapping powers — merging (interface-only) and unions/tuples (type-only) — are exactly where the \"just use whichever\" advice breaks down.</p><div class=\"key\"><p>Same job for object shapes, but two superpowers don't overlap: only <code>interface</code> merges (enabling augmentation), and only <code>type</code> expresses unions, tuples, and computed types. Default to <code>interface</code> for extendable contracts, <code>type</code> for everything shaped or unioned.</p></div>"},
  "discriminated-union": {"teach":"<p>At its core, a discriminated union is a collection of object shapes where every shape carries a little <strong>label</strong> field, so that checking that one label tells TypeScript — with certainty — exactly which shape you're holding.</p><h4>Dissecting the idea</h4><p>It's a <em>union</em> (a value is one of several types) of <em>object types</em> that all share one property typed as a <strong>literal</strong> (the <em>discriminant</em>, conventionally <code>kind</code> or <code>type</code>). For example:</p><ul><li><code>{ kind: 'ok'; data: string }</code></li><li><code>{ kind: 'err'; msg: string }</code></li></ul><p>The magic is that <code>'ok'</code> and <code>'err'</code> are not the broad type <code>string</code> — they are specific literal types. So when you write <code>switch (s.kind)</code> and land in <code>case 'ok'</code>, TypeScript <strong>narrows</strong> <code>s</code> to exactly the first shape, and <code>s.data</code> is available and type-safe. Inside that branch, <code>s.msg</code> wouldn't even exist.</p><div class=\"analogy\"><p>Think of mail sorting. Every envelope has a colored stamp in the corner — red for invoices, blue for letters, green for parcels. The sorter doesn't open the envelope to guess what's inside; one glance at the stamp routes it to the right bin, and now they know precisely what tools that bin needs. The discriminant is the colored stamp.</p></div><h4>Why it matters in practice</h4><p>This pattern is the backbone of typed <strong>reducers</strong> (Redux actions tagged by <code>type</code>), <strong>state machines</strong> (each state is a variant), and <strong>result/error modeling</strong> (success vs failure). It lets you replace fragile runtime guessing with compiler-verified routing.</p><h4>The exhaustiveness superpower</h4><p>Pair the <code>default</code> branch with an assignment to <code>never</code>:</p><ul><li><code>default: const _e: never = s; return _e;</code></li></ul><p>If you've handled every variant, <code>s</code> has been narrowed to <code>never</code> by the time control reaches <code>default</code>, so the assignment compiles. But the day someone adds a third variant — say <code>{ kind: 'loading' }</code> — and forgets to handle it, <code>s</code> is no longer <code>never</code> there, and the build <strong>breaks</strong>. The compiler becomes your checklist for future changes.</p><h4>The trap</h4><p>This only works when the discriminant is a <strong>literal</strong> type. If you type the tag as plain <code>string</code> (or forget <code>as const</code> somewhere), there's nothing specific to narrow on, and every branch stays the full union. Keep the tag literal.</p><div class=\"key\"><p>Give each variant a shared literal tag, <code>switch</code> on it, and TypeScript narrows each branch to exactly one shape — then a <code>never</code> default turns \"forgot a case\" into a compile error instead of a production bug.</p></div>"},
  "narrowing": {"teach":"<p>At its core, narrowing is TypeScript watching your runtime checks and <strong>shrinking</strong> a broad type down to a precise one inside the branch where that check is true. You write an ordinary <code>if</code>; the compiler quietly updates what it believes about the variable.</p><h4>How it works</h4><p>This is <strong>control-flow analysis</strong>. TypeScript reads your code path by path and tracks the type of each variable at each point. When a guard proves something, the type gets refined for the rest of that branch:</p><ul><li><code>typeof x === 'string'</code> → <code>x</code> is <code>string</code> here</li><li><code>x instanceof Date</code> → <code>x</code> is <code>Date</code></li><li><code>'meow' in pet</code> → <code>pet</code> has <code>meow</code></li><li>truthiness (<code>if (x)</code> removes <code>null</code>/<code>undefined</code>/<code>0</code>/<code>''</code>)</li><li>equality, discriminant <code>switch</code>es, user-defined predicates, and assertion functions</li></ul><p>In the worked example, after <code>if (typeof x === 'string')</code> you may call <code>x.toUpperCase()</code> with no cast; in the <code>else</code>, <code>x</code> is <code>number</code> and <code>x.toFixed(2)</code> is safe.</p><div class=\"analogy\"><p>Imagine a detective narrowing a suspect list. \"The culprit is left-handed\" eliminates half the room; \"and wears glasses\" eliminates more. Each verified fact <em>shrinks</em> the pool until only valid possibilities remain. Narrowing is the compiler being that detective — every guard is a clue that removes types from consideration.</p></div><h4>Why it matters: it's verified, not promised</h4><p>Narrowing is the disciplined alternative to <code>as</code> assertions. When you write <code>x as string</code>, you're making an <em>unverified promise</em> — the compiler trusts you blindly. Narrowing is the opposite: the compiler <strong>proves</strong> the type from a real runtime check, so there's no way for it to be a lie. Prefer narrowing wherever you can; reach for assertions only when the compiler genuinely can't see what you know.</p><h4>The trap: narrowing can evaporate</h4><p>Narrowing lives inside a contiguous flow the compiler can reason about. It can be <strong>invalidated when crossing into a closure or callback</strong>, because the compiler can't prove the variable wasn't reassigned in between — especially a <code>let</code> captured by an async callback. So a value you narrowed before a callback may appear wide again <em>inside</em> it:</p><ul><li>Fix by copying to a <code>const</code> after narrowing, or re-checking inside the callback.</li></ul><p>The compiler is conservative on purpose: if it can't <em>prove</em> the narrowed type still holds, it backs off rather than risk a false guarantee.</p><div class=\"key\"><p>Narrowing is compiler-verified type refinement driven by your runtime guards — safer than <code>as</code> because it's proven, not promised. Just remember it can reset across closures, so capture narrowed values in a <code>const</code> when a callback is involved.</p></div>"},
  "type-guard": {"teach":"<p>At its core, a user-defined type guard is a function that doesn't just return <code>true</code>/<code>false</code> — it returns a <strong>promise about a type</strong>, written as <code>arg is T</code>, and TypeScript uses that promise to narrow for you at the call site.</p><h4>The two flavors</h4><p><strong>Type predicate</strong> — <code>function isCat(p: Pet): p is Cat</code>. The return type <code>p is Cat</code> tells the compiler: \"if I return <code>true</code>, treat <code>p</code> as a <code>Cat</code>.\" So after <code>if (isCat(pet)) pet.meow()</code>, <code>pet</code> is narrowed to <code>Cat</code> inside the block — you've packaged reusable narrowing logic into one named function.</p><p><strong>Assertion signature</strong> — <code>function assertIsCat(p: Pet): asserts p is Cat</code>. Instead of returning a boolean, it <em>throws</em> if the condition fails. After the call, narrowing applies to <strong>everything that follows</strong> (no <code>if</code> needed), because if execution reached the next line, the assertion must have held.</p><div class=\"analogy\"><p>A type predicate is a bouncer who checks your ID and then <em>stamps your hand</em> — everyone past that point can see the stamp and treats you as verified. An assertion signature is a bouncer who simply throws you out if your ID is fake: if you're still in the room, you're definitely allowed to be.</p></div><h4>The dangerous part: TypeScript trusts you</h4><p>Here is the crucial fact. The compiler does <strong>not</strong> verify that your function body actually proves the predicate. It takes the signature on faith.</p><ul><li><code>function isCat(p): p is Cat { return true; }</code> compiles cleanly — and <strong>lies</strong>. Every value now gets treated as a <code>Cat</code>, and any <code>.meow()</code> call may blow up at runtime.</li></ul><p>So a guard is a hole you deliberately punch in the type system, with a promise to fill it correctly. Treat guard bodies as <strong>trusted, well-tested code</strong> — they centralize narrowing, which means a single wrong guard silently corrupts safety everywhere it's used. The honest worked-example check, <code>(p as Cat).meow !== undefined</code>, actually inspects a distinguishing property, which is what makes the promise true.</p><h4>A modern convenience</h4><p>As of TypeScript 5.5, the compiler can <strong>infer simple predicates automatically</strong>. A function like <code>x => x !== null</code> used in <code>.filter()</code> now narrows the resulting array without you writing an explicit <code>x is T</code> — removing a long-standing papercut where filtered arrays kept their nullable element type.</p><div class=\"key\"><p>A type guard returns <code>arg is T</code> (or <code>asserts arg is T</code>) to teach the compiler how to narrow — but the compiler never checks your logic, so a wrong guard compiles and lies. Write them carefully, test them hard, and let TS 5.5+ infer the simple ones for you.</p></div>"},
  "keyof": {"teach":"<p>At its core, <code>keyof</code> hands you the list of an object type's property <strong>names</strong>, and indexed access <code>T[K]</code> hands you the <strong>type stored at</strong> one of those names. They're the type-level equivalents of \"what keys does this object have?\" and \"what's the value at this key?\"</p><h4>Dissecting the two operators</h4><ul><li><code>keyof T</code> produces a <strong>union</strong> of <code>T</code>'s public keys. For <code>{ a: number; b: string }</code>, <code>keyof T</code> is <code>'a' | 'b'</code>.</li><li><code>T[K]</code> is <strong>indexed access</strong>: <code>T['a']</code> is <code>number</code>. If <code>K</code> is a union of keys, you get a union of the corresponding value types.</li></ul><p>Together they let you write generic property access that's fully type-safe — pass any valid key, get back exactly the right value type, no casts.</p><div class=\"analogy\"><p>Picture a building directory in a lobby. <code>keyof</code> is the <em>list of room numbers</em> on the board. <code>T[K]</code> is walking to room <code>K</code> and seeing <em>what's actually in that room</em>. You can't ask for a room that isn't on the board (invalid key = type error), and once you pick a real room, you know precisely what you'll find.</p></div><h4>The array trick: T[number]</h4><p>This is the one to internalize. For an array or tuple, <code>T[number]</code> gives the <strong>element type</strong> — because you're indexing \"at some number.\" Combine it with <code>as const</code> and <code>typeof</code> to derive a literal union from runtime data:</p><ul><li><code>const ROLES = ['admin', 'user'] as const</code></li><li><code>type Role = typeof ROLES[number]</code> → <code>'admin' | 'user'</code></li></ul><p>Now your runtime array and your type are the <strong>same single source of truth</strong>. Add a role to the array and the union updates automatically — no second list to keep in sync.</p><h4>The trap: index signatures collapse keyof</h4><p>If a type has a <strong>string index signature</strong> — <code>{ [k: string]: number }</code> — then <code>keyof T</code> is <strong>not</strong> the specific keys you wrote. It collapses to <code>string | number</code> (the <code>number</code> appears because JS object keys are strings, and numeric keys coerce). So if you expected <code>keyof</code> to return your hand-written literal keys but the type also has an index signature, you'll get the broad <code>string | number</code> instead and your precise narrowing won't work.</p><div class=\"key\"><p><code>keyof T</code> is the union of keys, <code>T[K]</code> is the value type at a key, and <code>T[number]</code> extracts an array's element type — the secret to turning an <code>as const</code> array into a literal union. Just beware: a string index signature makes <code>keyof</code> collapse to <code>string | number</code>.</p></div>"},
  "mapped-type": {"teach":"<p>At its core, a mapped type is a <strong>loop over an object's keys</strong> that rebuilds a new object type, transforming each property as it goes. It's a \"for-each key\" — but in type space, not at runtime.</p><h4>Reading the syntax</h4><p>The shape is <code>{ [K in keyof T]: ... }</code>. Let's dissect it:</p><ul><li><code>K in keyof T</code> means \"for each key <code>K</code> in <code>T</code>'s key union.\"</li><li>The right-hand side is the new value type for that key — often <code>T[K]</code> (kept) or something derived from it.</li></ul><p>You can also tweak <strong>modifiers</strong>: add or strip <code>readonly</code> and <code>?</code> (optionality) with <code>+</code>/<code>-</code>. So <code>{ [K in keyof T]-?: T[K] }</code> removes optionality (that's literally how <code>Required</code> works), and <code>+readonly</code> adds immutability (that's <code>Readonly</code>).</p><div class=\"analogy\"><p>Think of an assembly line relabeling jars. Each jar (property) rolls past a station; the station can put a \"do not open\" sticker on it (<code>readonly</code>), mark it optional, rename its label, or even reject it off the belt. The mapped type is the conveyor that visits every jar and decides what the rebuilt set looks like.</p></div><h4>The utility types are just mapped types</h4><p>This is the unlock: <code>Partial</code>, <code>Readonly</code>, <code>Pick</code>, and <code>Record</code> are all mapped types under the hood. Once you see the loop, you can write your own.</p><h4>Key remapping (TS 4.1+)</h4><p>You can <strong>rename</strong> keys with an <code>as</code> clause: <code>{ [K in keyof T as NewKey]: ... }</code>. The worked example builds getter names:</p><ul><li><code>[K in keyof T as `get${Capitalize&lt;string &amp; K&gt;}`]: () =&gt; T[K]</code></li><li>turns <code>{ name: string }</code> into <code>{ getName: () =&gt; string }</code>.</li></ul><p>You can also <strong>filter</strong> keys: remap a key to <code>never</code> and it drops out of the result entirely — a clean way to remove properties by condition.</p><h4>The trap: homomorphic vs not</h4><p>A mapped type written <em>directly</em> over <code>keyof T</code> is <strong>homomorphic</strong> — it preserves the original's modifiers and even its array-ness (mapping over an array yields an array-like). But if you map over an <em>arbitrary</em> key union instead (as <code>Record&lt;K, V&gt;</code> does — it's <code>{ [P in K]: V }</code> over a free <code>K</code>, not <code>keyof T</code>), it's <strong>not</strong> homomorphic, so <code>readonly</code>/<code>?</code> and array-ness are <em>not</em> carried over. Expecting preservation there is a common surprise.</p><div class=\"key\"><p>A mapped type loops over <code>keyof T</code> to rebuild an object, optionally flipping <code>readonly</code>/<code>?</code> and remapping or filtering keys with <code>as</code>. It's the engine behind <code>Partial</code> and friends — and only the homomorphic form (over <code>keyof T</code>) preserves modifiers and array-ness.</p></div>"},
  "conditional-type": {"teach":"<p>At its core, a conditional type is an <strong>if/else for types</strong>: <code>T extends U ? X : Y</code> means \"if <code>T</code> fits into <code>U</code>, the type is <code>X</code>, otherwise <code>Y</code>.\" And with <code>infer</code>, that same expression can <strong>reach in and extract</strong> a piece of another type.</p><h4>Dissecting the syntax</h4><ul><li><code>T extends U</code> is an <em>assignability</em> test, not inheritance — \"is every <code>T</code> also a <code>U</code>?\"</li><li><code>? X : Y</code> picks the branch.</li><li><code>infer R</code>, written <em>inside</em> the <code>extends</code> clause, declares a fresh type variable that TypeScript fills in by pattern-matching.</li></ul><p>In the worked example, <code>T extends (infer E)[] ? E : T</code> reads as: \"if <code>T</code> is an array of <em>some</em> element type — call it <code>E</code> — give me <code>E</code>; otherwise give me <code>T</code>.\" So <code>ElementType&lt;string[]&gt;</code> is <code>string</code>. This <code>infer</code> mechanism is exactly how <code>ReturnType</code>, <code>Parameters</code>, and <code>Awaited</code> pull the return type, argument types, and resolved value out of other types.</p><div class=\"analogy\"><p><code>infer</code> is like regex capture groups. <code>(\\d+)px</code> doesn't just check that a string ends in <code>px</code> — it captures the number for you to use. <code>(infer E)[]</code> doesn't just check \"is this an array,\" it captures the element type into <code>E</code> so you can return it.</p></div><h4>The subtle part: distribution</h4><p>When the checked type is a <strong>naked type parameter</strong> (just <code>T</code>, not wrapped) and you feed it a <em>union</em>, the conditional <strong>distributes</strong>: it applies to each union member separately, then unions the results. So <code>ToArray&lt;string | number&gt;</code> where <code>ToArray&lt;T&gt; = T extends any ? T[] : never</code> becomes <code>string[] | number[]</code>, not <code>(string | number)[]</code>. Often that's what you want — but often it isn't.</p><h4>Turning distribution off</h4><p>Wrap <strong>both sides in a 1-tuple</strong> to stop it: <code>[T] extends [U] ? X : Y</code>. Now <code>T</code> isn't naked, so the whole union is tested <em>atomically</em>. This is also the canonical way to <strong>detect <code>never</code></strong>: <code>[T] extends [never] ? ... </code> works, whereas the unwrapped form misbehaves because a conditional over <code>never</code> distributes over zero members and short-circuits to <code>never</code>.</p><h4>The trap</h4><p>Forgetting distribution is a classic source of \"why is my type a weird union?\" bugs. When you want to reason about a union as a single thing, reach for the tuple wrapper.</p><div class=\"key\"><p><code>T extends U ? X : Y</code> is a type-level if/else, and <code>infer</code> captures matched sub-types (powering <code>ReturnType</code> and <code>Awaited</code>). Remember that a naked type parameter distributes over unions — wrap both sides in <code>[ ]</code> when you need to test a union atomically or detect <code>never</code>.</p></div>"},
  "utility-types": {"teach":"<p>At its core, utility types are TypeScript's <strong>built-in toolbox of type transformers</strong> — ready-made helpers that take an existing type and reshape it, so you rarely write the same boilerplate twice.</p><h4>The main families</h4><ul><li><strong>Object shapers</strong> — <code>Partial&lt;T&gt;</code> (all props optional), <code>Required&lt;T&gt;</code> (all required), <code>Readonly&lt;T&gt;</code> (all immutable).</li><li><strong>Selectors</strong> — <code>Pick&lt;T, K&gt;</code> (keep only keys <code>K</code>), <code>Omit&lt;T, K&gt;</code> (drop keys <code>K</code>), <code>Record&lt;K, V&gt;</code> (build an object from keys to a value type).</li><li><strong>Union filters</strong> — <code>Exclude&lt;U, X&gt;</code> (remove members), <code>Extract&lt;U, X&gt;</code> (keep matching members), <code>NonNullable&lt;T&gt;</code> (strip <code>null</code>/<code>undefined</code>).</li><li><strong>Function/promise extractors</strong> — <code>ReturnType</code>, <code>Parameters</code>, <code>InstanceType</code>, <code>Awaited</code> (unwrap a Promise, even nested ones — <code>Awaited&lt;Promise&lt;Promise&lt;number&gt;&gt;&gt;</code> is <code>number</code>).</li></ul><div class=\"analogy\"><p>They're like the standard kitchen attachments that come with a stand mixer. You <em>could</em> machine your own dough hook, but the whisk, paddle, and hook ship in the box and cover most jobs. And when you need something exotic, you now understand the mount well enough to build a custom attachment.</p></div><h4>The big insight: they aren't magic</h4><p>Every utility type is built from the <strong>mapped and conditional types</strong> you've already met. <code>Partial</code> is a mapped type adding <code>?</code>. <code>Omit</code> is <em>literally</em> <code>Pick&lt;T, Exclude&lt;keyof T, K&gt;&gt;</code> — \"pick all keys except the ones to remove.\" Once you see that, the toolbox stops being a memorization exercise: you can read the lib source, and you can compose your own — <code>DeepPartial</code>, <code>RequireOne</code>, etc.</p><h4>They compose</h4><p><code>Partial&lt;Pick&lt;User, 'name' | 'email'&gt;&gt;</code> reads as \"an optional patch object containing only name and email.\" Stacking utilities is the everyday way to express precise shapes.</p><h4>The trap: Omit doesn't validate its keys</h4><p>Here's the sharp edge. <code>Pick&lt;T, K&gt;</code> constrains <code>K extends keyof T</code>, so a typo'd key is a compile error. But <code>Omit&lt;T, K&gt;</code> types its key parameter as <code>keyof any</code> (i.e. <code>string | number | symbol</code>) — deliberately, so you can omit keys that may not exist. The downside: <code>Omit&lt;User, 'emial'&gt;</code> (typo) <strong>silently omits nothing</strong> and gives you back the full type, no error. Double-check your <code>Omit</code> keys.</p><div class=\"key\"><p>Utility types are composable helpers built from mapped/conditional types — knowing that lets you read and extend them. Watch the asymmetry: <code>Pick</code> validates its keys, but <code>Omit</code> does not, so a typo there fails silently.</p></div>"},
  "unknown-type": {"teach":"<p>At its core, <code>unknown</code> is the <strong>honest \"I don't know what this is yet\"</strong> type — it holds any value, but forces you to check before you touch it. <code>any</code> is the <strong>reckless</strong> sibling — it also holds anything, but it switches type checking <em>off</em> for whatever it touches.</p><h4>unknown: the safe top type</h4><p>A <strong>top type</strong> is one that every value is assignable to — the widest possible type. Both <code>unknown</code> and <code>any</code> are top types in that sense. The difference is what you're <em>allowed to do</em>:</p><ul><li>With <code>unknown</code>, you can store anything, but you <strong>cannot operate on it</strong> — no property access, no calls, no arithmetic — until you <em>narrow</em> it with a guard.</li><li>With <code>any</code>, the compiler lets you do <strong>anything</strong>, and worse, <code>any</code> is <em>contagious</em>: it silently spreads through every expression it flows into, quietly disabling checks far beyond the one line you wrote.</li></ul><div class=\"analogy\"><p><code>unknown</code> is a sealed package on your doorstep: you accept it, but you don't shake it, open it, or plug it in until you've inspected the label. <code>any</code> is opening the package blindfolded and assuming it's whatever you hoped for — and then handing pieces of it to everyone in the house, blindfolded too.</p></div><h4>Where to use unknown</h4><p>Put <code>unknown</code> at every <strong>untrusted boundary</strong> — places where data enters your program and you can't trust its shape:</p><ul><li><code>JSON.parse(s)</code> — could be anything.</li><li>Network responses.</li><li><code>catch (e: unknown)</code> — caught errors aren't guaranteed to be <code>Error</code>.</li></ul><p>Then narrow: <code>if (typeof data === 'object' &amp;&amp; data &amp;&amp; 'id' in data)</code> proves enough structure to safely read <code>data.id</code>. The compiler walks you through validating before trusting.</p><h4>Where (rarely) to use any</h4><p>Reserve <code>any</code> for genuine escape hatches — gnarly third-party types, migration scaffolding — and <strong>isolate it</strong> so its contagion can't spread. The trap is reaching for <code>any</code> just to silence an error; it does far more damage than the one line suggests, because it defeats checking everywhere that value travels.</p><h4>Its mirror image: never</h4><p>If <code>unknown</code> is the top type (everything fits), <code>never</code> is the <strong>bottom type</strong> — <em>nothing</em> fits, no value inhabits it. They're the two poles of the type lattice: <code>unknown</code> says \"could be any value,\" <code>never</code> says \"can be no value.\"</p><div class=\"key\"><p>Use <code>unknown</code> at every untrusted input and narrow before use — it keeps the type system on. Avoid <code>any</code>: it doesn't just relax one line, it silently turns off checking for everything it touches.</p></div>"},
  "never-type": {"teach":"<p>At its core, <code>never</code> is the type of a value that <strong>can't exist</strong>. It's not \"empty\" or \"nothing returned\" — it's the type you give to a code path that, logically, should be impossible to reach.</p><h4>The bottom type, dissected</h4><p><code>never</code> is the <strong>bottom type</strong>, the mirror image of <code>unknown</code>'s top type. Three facts define it:</p><ul><li><strong>No value inhabits it.</strong> You can never produce a value of type <code>never</code>.</li><li><strong>It's assignable <em>to</em> every type.</strong> Since it's impossible, it vacuously satisfies any expected type — \"a thing that can't happen fits anywhere.\"</li><li><strong>Nothing (except <code>never</code>) is assignable <em>to</em> it.</strong> You can't store a <code>string</code> or even <code>undefined</code> into a <code>never</code> slot.</li></ul><div class=\"analogy\"><p>Think of <code>never</code> as a road sign reading \"BRIDGE OUT — NO CROSSING.\" No traveler is ever on the far side (no value inhabits it). And if your map-routing algorithm ever computes a path <em>onto</em> that road, you know your map is wrong — which is exactly how the compiler uses it to catch bugs.</p></div><h4>Where it shows up</h4><ul><li>Functions that <strong>never return</strong> — they <code>throw</code> or loop forever: <code>function fail(m: string): never { throw new Error(m); }</code>.</li><li><strong>Impossible narrowings</strong> — after you've eliminated every possibility in a union, the leftover type is <code>never</code>.</li><li><strong>Filtered-out mapped-type keys</strong> — remapping a key to <code>never</code> deletes it from the result.</li></ul><h4>The killer application: exhaustiveness</h4><p>Assign a discriminated-union variable to <code>never</code> in a <code>default</code> branch:</p><ul><li><code>default: const _exhaustive: never = action;</code></li></ul><p>If you've handled every case, <code>action</code> is already narrowed to <code>never</code> there, so it compiles. The moment a teammate adds a new variant and forgets to handle it, <code>action</code> is no longer <code>never</code>, that assignment <strong>fails to compile</strong>, and the build points right at the gap. Your switch becomes self-policing.</p><h4>The trap: never vs void</h4><p>Don't confuse them. <code>void</code> means \"this function <em>does</em> return, but you should ignore the value\" (like a logger). <code>never</code> means \"this function <strong>does not return at all</strong>\" (it throws or hangs). A function typed <code>void</code> reaches its caller's next line; one typed <code>never</code> never does.</p><div class=\"key\"><p><code>never</code> is the type with no values — assignable to everything, accepting nothing. Its highest-value use is the <code>default</code>-branch exhaustiveness check that turns a forgotten union case into a compile error. And it is not <code>void</code>: <code>never</code> means \"doesn't return,\" <code>void</code> means \"returns nothing useful.\"</p></div>"},
  "type-assertion": {"teach":"<p>At its core, a type assertion is you telling the compiler <strong>\"trust me, this is a <code>T</code>\"</strong> — with <em>nothing</em> backing it up at runtime. It changes what the compiler believes, and changes <strong>nothing</strong> about the actual bytes in memory.</p><h4>x as T — compile-time only</h4><p><code>x as T</code> reinterprets a value's type during type-checking and then <strong>vanishes</strong> when your code compiles to JavaScript. There is no conversion, no validation, no coercion. TypeScript will only let you assert between types that <strong>overlap</strong> (one is assignable to the other in some direction). If they're unrelated, you must <em>double-assert</em> through <code>unknown</code>: <code>raw as unknown as Config</code> — which is a deliberate code smell, a flashing sign that you're overriding the compiler completely.</p><div class=\"analogy\"><p>An assertion is like crossing out the label on a shipping box and writing \"FRAGILE GLASS\" yourself. The handlers now <em>treat</em> it as glass — but you didn't change the contents. If it was actually bricks, the new label fooled everyone and someone gets hurt downstream. The label (type) changed; the contents (runtime value) did not.</p></div><h4>The non-null assertion: x!</h4><p><code>x!</code> is a focused assertion: \"this value is not <code>null</code> or <code>undefined</code>.\" Like <code>as</code>, it's purely compile-time — <strong>no runtime guard</strong> is inserted. <code>document.getElementById('app')!</code> tells the compiler the element exists; if it doesn't, you get a runtime crash the type system was <em>designed</em> to prevent.</p><h4>Why this is risky</h4><p>Both forms are <strong>unverified promises</strong>. Compare them to narrowing, which is <em>verified</em> by a real runtime check. With an assertion, if you're wrong, the safety net is gone and the error surfaces at runtime — exactly where types were supposed to save you. So the rule is: <strong>prefer narrowing or real runtime validation</strong> (a guard, a schema check), and reserve assertions for things the compiler genuinely cannot see:</p><ul><li>Framework-initialized fields (e.g. a class property a DI container sets).</li><li>DOM elements you <em>know</em> exist from the surrounding HTML.</li><li>Refs that are populated later in a lifecycle.</li></ul><h4>The trap</h4><p>Don't think <code>as</code> behaves like a C# cast or a C conversion. In those languages a cast can convert or check at runtime. In TypeScript, <code>as</code> does <strong>absolutely nothing at runtime</strong> — no rounding, no boxing, no check. The value is byte-for-byte unchanged; only the compiler's opinion of it moved.</p><div class=\"key\"><p>Assertions (<code>as T</code>, <code>x!</code>) are compile-time-only, unverified promises with zero runtime effect — being wrong gives you the very crash types exist to prevent. Reach for narrowing or real validation first, and limit assertions to things the compiler truly can't see.</p></div>"},
  "strict-null-checks": {"teach":"<p>At its core, <code>strictNullChecks</code> makes <code>null</code> and <code>undefined</code> their <strong>own distinct types</strong> that you must declare and handle on purpose — instead of letting them silently hide inside every other type.</p><h4>What it actually changes</h4><p>Without the flag, <code>null</code> and <code>undefined</code> are members of <em>every</em> type — a <code>string</code> can secretly be <code>null</code>, and the compiler won't warn you when you call <code>.length</code> on it. Turn the flag <strong>on</strong>, and those two values are <strong>removed from every other type's domain</strong>. If a value can be missing, you must say so explicitly:</p><ul><li><code>string</code> means \"definitely a string.\"</li><li><code>string | undefined</code> means \"a string, or maybe nothing\" — and now you're <em>forced</em> to handle the nothing before dereferencing.</li></ul><p>In the worked example, <code>function len(s: string | null)</code> can't just do <code>s.length</code> — you must write <code>s?.length ?? 0</code>, handling the null path. The optional chaining <code>?.</code> short-circuits on null, and <code>??</code> supplies a fallback.</p><div class=\"analogy\"><p>Without the flag, every variable is a box that <em>might</em> be empty, but the labels never mention it — so you keep reaching in and occasionally grabbing air (a runtime crash). With it on, any box that can be empty is <strong>labeled \"may be empty,\"</strong> and the system won't let you reach in without first checking. The bugs move from 3am production pages to your editor's red squiggles.</p></div><h4>Why it's the highest-value flag</h4><p>The \"billion-dollar mistake\" — null reference errors — is the single most common class of runtime crash in typed languages. <code>strictNullChecks</code> eliminates the bulk of it at <em>compile time</em>. It's the most impactful member of the <code>strict</code> family by a wide margin.</p><h4>What strict bundles</h4><p>Setting <code>strict: true</code> turns on a whole group together: <code>strictNullChecks</code>, <code>noImplicitAny</code>, <code>strictFunctionTypes</code>, <code>strictPropertyInitialization</code>, <code>useUnknownInCatchVariables</code>, and more. It's the recommended baseline for any serious project.</p><h4>The trap: index access is still unchecked</h4><p>Here's the gap people miss. <code>strict</code> does <strong>not</strong> make array and record reads null-safe. <code>arr[i]</code> is typed as the element type — <em>not</em> <code>element | undefined</code> — even though <code>i</code> might be out of bounds. To close that hole you must separately enable <code>noUncheckedIndexedAccess</code>, which adds <code>| undefined</code> to indexed reads and forces you to check.</p><div class=\"key\"><p><code>strictNullChecks</code> pulls <code>null</code>/<code>undefined</code> out of every type so you must handle them explicitly — the biggest single win against runtime crashes. But it doesn't guard index access; pair it with <code>noUncheckedIndexedAccess</code> for truly safe array and record reads.</p></div>"},
  "as-const": {"teach":"<p>At its core, <code>as const</code> tells TypeScript: <strong>\"don't generalize this — keep the exact, most specific, read-only version of what I wrote.\"</strong> Normally the compiler <em>widens</em> values (a <code>'GET'</code> literal becomes the broad type <code>string</code>); <code>as const</code> switches that off.</p><h4>What it does, piece by piece</h4><ul><li><strong>Primitives stay literal.</strong> <code>const x = 'GET'</code> is typed <code>string</code>, but <code>const x = 'GET' as const</code> is typed <code>'GET'</code> — the exact value.</li><li><strong>Object properties become deeply <code>readonly</code>.</strong> Nothing in the structure can be reassigned, all the way down.</li><li><strong>Arrays become <code>readonly</code> tuples.</strong> <code>['GET', 'POST']</code> isn't <code>string[]</code> anymore; it's the fixed-length <code>readonly ['GET', 'POST']</code>.</li></ul><div class=\"analogy\"><p>Default inference is like a tailor who, hearing \"I want a blue shirt,\" gives you a generic blue shirt — any blue will do. <code>as const</code> is saying \"I want <em>this exact</em> navy, size M, no buttons changed, ever.\" You lose flexibility but gain a precise, locked-in specification you can build guarantees on.</p></div><h4>The single-source-of-truth pattern</h4><p>This is the killer use. A runtime constant can double as the definition of a literal union:</p><ul><li><code>const METHODS = ['GET', 'POST'] as const</code></li><li><code>type Method = typeof METHODS[number]</code> → <code>'GET' | 'POST'</code></li></ul><p>The array exists at runtime (you can iterate it, validate against it) <em>and</em> drives the type. For object maps you use <code>typeof X[keyof typeof X]</code> to derive the union of values. Add an entry to the data and the type updates automatically — there's no second list to keep in sync, which is where bugs love to hide.</p><h4>Why it's the modern enum replacement</h4><p>Instead of a TypeScript <code>enum</code> (which emits extra runtime machinery and has type-safety quirks), <code>const X = {...} as const</code> plus a derived union gives you a <strong>real value object</strong> you can use at runtime <em>and</em> a <strong>precise literal type</strong> — with <strong>zero extra emit</strong> beyond the data you already wrote. You get the best of both worlds and nothing erased gets lost.</p><h4>The trap: readonly meets mutable APIs</h4><p>Because <code>as const</code> produces a <code>readonly</code> tuple, passing it to a function that wants a <strong>mutable</strong> array (e.g. <code>(arr: string[]) => ...</code>) is a <strong>type error</strong> — TypeScript won't hand a frozen tuple to something that might push to it. Either change the parameter to accept <code>readonly string[]</code>, or copy the array with a spread (<code>[...METHODS]</code>) to get a mutable version.</p><div class=\"key\"><p><code>as const</code> freezes values to their narrowest literal, <code>readonly</code> form — the idiomatic way to make one constant be both runtime data and a derived literal union (<code>typeof X[number]</code>), and the preferred replacement for <code>enum</code>. Just remember its <code>readonly</code>-ness clashes with APIs expecting mutable arrays.</p></div>"},
  "enum-vs-union": {"teach":"<p>At its core, the choice is between a construct that <strong>leaves real JavaScript behind</strong> (an <code>enum</code>) and one that <strong>disappears completely</strong> after compilation (a literal union). That single difference drives almost everything else.</p><h4>What an enum actually compiles to</h4><p>A TypeScript <code>enum</code> is not just types — it emits a <strong>runtime object</strong>. Numeric enums even generate a <em>reverse mapping</em> (so <code>Color[0]</code> gives back <code>'Red'</code>), doubling the emitted code. Consequences:</p><ul><li>It <strong>can't be erased</strong>, so it adds bundle weight even if you only wanted the type.</li><li>Numeric enums are <strong>type-unsafe</strong>: any <code>number</code> is assignable to a numeric enum type, so <code>5</code> sneaks in where only defined members should be allowed.</li></ul><h4>What a literal union is</h4><p>A union like <code>'active' | 'done'</code> lives <strong>only in type space</strong>. After compilation it's gone — zero runtime footprint. It's just a constraint the compiler enforces while you code.</p><div class=\"analogy\"><p>An <code>enum</code> is like building a physical filing cabinet that ships with your product — useful, but it takes up space in the truck whether or not anyone opens it. A literal union is like a rule written on the whiteboard during design: it shapes how everyone builds, then you wipe the board clean and ship nothing extra.</p></div><h4>The modern idiom</h4><p>Today's code favors <strong><code>const X = {...} as const</code> plus a derived union</strong>, or just a plain string-literal union. The <code>as const</code> approach gives you a real value object to iterate <em>and</em> a precise type — without the enum's runtime baggage or numeric pitfalls. The worked example shows exactly this: <code>const Status = { Active: 'active', Done: 'done' } as const</code>, then <code>type Status = typeof Status[keyof typeof Status]</code>.</p><h4>The 2026 tooling shift</h4><p>This isn't just style — the toolchain is moving against enums. As of TS 5.8, the <strong><code>--erasableSyntaxOnly</code></strong> flag (aligned with Node.js's native type-stripping, where the runtime just deletes type syntax rather than transforming it) <strong>errors on all enums</strong> — including <code>const enum</code> — plus namespaces that contain runtime code and constructor parameter properties. These are the TypeScript features that <em>generate</em> JavaScript and thus can't simply be erased.</p><h4>The trap: const enum</h4><p>People reach for <code>const enum</code> to get \"free\" inlining (members substituted directly, no object emitted). But it <strong>breaks under <code>isolatedModules</code>, Babel, and esbuild</strong> — which compile files in isolation and can't see across to inline the values — and it's now <strong>rejected by <code>erasableSyntaxOnly</code></strong>. The result is surprising, environment-dependent build failures. Avoid it.</p><div class=\"key\"><p>Enums emit runtime JavaScript (with numeric-enum type holes); literal unions vanish at compile time. Prefer <code>as const</code> objects with a derived union — and avoid <code>enum</code>/<code>const enum</code> entirely, since modern erasable-syntax tooling (TS 5.8 <code>--erasableSyntaxOnly</code>, Node type-stripping) rejects them.</p></div>"},
  "declaration-merging": {"teach":"<p>At its core, declaration merging is TypeScript's rule that <strong>two declarations with the same name combine into one</strong>. Declare an <code>interface Foo</code> twice, and instead of an error you get a single <code>Foo</code> containing the union of both bodies.</p><h4>The mechanism</h4><p>When the compiler sees multiple <code>interface</code> (or <code>namespace</code>) declarations of the same name in the same scope, it <strong>merges</strong> their members:</p><ul><li><code>interface W { a: number }</code></li><li><code>interface W { b: number }</code></li><li>Result: <code>W</code> is <code>{ a: number; b: number }</code>.</li></ul><div class=\"analogy\"><p>Think of a community bulletin board labeled \"WEEKEND PLANS.\" One neighbor pins a note about the picnic, another adds a note about the cleanup. Nobody tears down the first to add the second — the board <em>accumulates</em> all the notes under one heading. Interfaces are that bulletin board; each declaration pins more onto the same name.</p></div><h4>Why this matters: augmentation</h4><p>Merging is the engine behind <strong>module augmentation</strong> and <strong>global augmentation</strong> — the ability to <em>reopen</em> a type you don't own and add to it without forking the library. The classic case is teaching Express that requests now carry a <code>user</code>:</p><ul><li><code>declare module 'express' { interface Request { user?: { id: string } } }</code></li></ul><p>Your declaration merges into Express's own <code>Request</code> interface, so <code>req.user</code> is now typed everywhere — and you never touched the library's source. This is how middleware authors, polyfills, and plugin ecosystems extend third-party and global types cleanly.</p><h4>The decisive contrast with type aliases</h4><p><code>type</code> aliases <strong>cannot merge</strong>. Declare <code>type Foo</code> twice and you get a \"Duplicate identifier\" error — they're sealed. This is the single most important reason to choose <code>interface</code> for <strong>any contract you expect third parties to extend</strong>. If you export your public shape as a <code>type</code>, consumers are locked out of augmenting it.</p><h4>Two gotchas to know</h4><ul><li><strong>The augmenting file must be a module.</strong> To augment a module, the file doing the augmenting needs a top-level <code>import</code> or <code>export</code> — otherwise TypeScript treats it as a global script and the <code>declare module</code> means something different (and usually won't work as intended).</li><li><strong>You can only augment what merges.</strong> If a library exported its shape as a <code>type</code> alias rather than an <code>interface</code>, you're stuck — there's no merging to hook into. Only <code>interface</code> and <code>namespace</code> declarations participate.</li></ul><div class=\"key\"><p>Declaration merging combines same-named <code>interface</code>/<code>namespace</code> declarations into one — the basis of module and global augmentation that lets you extend libraries without forking. Because <code>type</code> aliases can't merge, always export extendable public contracts as interfaces, and make your augmenting file a module.</p></div>"},
  "generic-constraint": {"teach":"<p>At its core, a generic constraint is a <strong>guardrail on a type parameter</strong>: <code>&lt;T extends U&gt;</code> says \"<code>T</code> can be anything — <em>as long as</em> it's at least a <code>U</code>.\" That guarantee then lets you safely use <code>U</code>'s members inside the function.</p><h4>Why you'd want one</h4><p>A plain generic <code>&lt;T&gt;</code> is maximally flexible but maximally ignorant — the compiler knows <em>nothing</em> about <code>T</code>, so you can't access any property of it. A constraint trades a little flexibility for knowledge:</p><ul><li><code>&lt;T extends { length: number }&gt;</code> — now you may read <code>x.length</code>, because every allowed <code>T</code> has it.</li><li>Callers are restricted to subtypes of the constraint, so passing a bare <code>number</code> (no <code>length</code>) is a compile error.</li></ul><div class=\"analogy\"><p>A constraint is like a job posting that says \"must have a driver's license.\" You don't know <em>who</em> will apply (the exact type), but you can confidently hand any hire the keys, because the requirement guarantees the one capability you depend on. Drop the requirement and you can't safely ask anyone to drive.</p></div><h4>The canonical pattern: K extends keyof T</h4><p>The most common constraint enables type-safe property access:</p><ul><li><code>function pluck&lt;T, K extends keyof T&gt;(o: T, k: K): T[K] { return o[k]; }</code></li><li><code>K extends keyof T</code> forces the key to be a <em>real</em> key of the object, and the return type <code>T[K]</code> is exactly the value type at that key.</li></ul><p>So <code>pluck(user, 'name')</code> returns a <code>string</code>, <code>pluck(user, 'age')</code> returns a <code>number</code>, and <code>pluck(user, 'xyz')</code> won't compile. Constraints also power <strong>generic defaults</strong> (<code>&lt;T = string&gt;</code>) and help <strong>drive inference</strong> from arguments.</p><h4>The subtle trap: the constraint is a ceiling, not the value</h4><p>Here's what bites people. Inside the function body, <code>T</code> is known only to be <em>some subtype of</em> the constraint — not the constraint itself, and not any concrete value of it. Why? Because the caller might pass something <strong>narrower</strong>. If you have <code>&lt;T extends { id: number }&gt;</code>, a caller could pass <code>{ id: number; name: string }</code>. So:</p><ul><li>You <em>can read</em> constraint members (<code>x.id</code> is safe — every <code>T</code> has it).</li><li>You <em>cannot produce</em> an arbitrary value of <code>T</code> — e.g. <code>return { id: 1 }</code> fails, because that bare object isn't assignable to a possibly-narrower <code>T</code> (it's missing <code>name</code> in the example above).</li></ul><p>The mental model: a constraint tells you the <strong>minimum</strong> <code>T</code> guarantees, never the exact shape.</p><div class=\"key\"><p><code>&lt;T extends U&gt;</code> limits callers to subtypes of <code>U</code> while letting you safely use <code>U</code>'s members — with <code>K extends keyof T</code> as the workhorse for type-safe access. Just remember the constraint is a floor you can read from, not a concrete type you can construct values of.</p></div>"}
});
